<section class="container">
  <h1>JusticeFusion advantages compared with general-purpose AI assistants</h1>
  <p>ChatGPT, Gemini, DeepSeek and similar tools are very useful for general tasks: explanations, ideas, writing, programming, summarization and everyday communication. However, legal work has different requirements: local regulations, concrete documents, source control, privacy, repeatability and the ability to work inside an organization’s infrastructure.</p>
  <p>JusticeFusion is designed specifically for that context: legal questions, local legal sources, user documents and environments where it matters where the answer comes from.</p>
  <h2>Key differences</h2>
  <p>General-purpose assistants provide breadth and flexibility, while JusticeFusion provides a legal-workflow-oriented approach with document grounding, retrieval-first context building and draft preparation ready for expert review.</p>
  <p>For organizations, a major difference is deployment flexibility: JusticeFusion can run locally, in a private cloud or offline, with intentional database updates and adaptation to internal systems.</p>
  <h2>Practical comparison</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap"><table><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>General-purpose AI assistants</th><th>JusticeFusion</th></tr><tr><td>Primary purpose</td><td>General tasks, writing, explanations, creative work and programming.</td><td>Legal research, document work, local legal context and draft preparation.</td></tr><tr><td>Local law</td><td>Can provide general information, but without guaranteed freshness or local specificity.</td><td>Can use a targeted database of local laws, regulations, case law and internal acts.</td></tr><tr><td>Private documents</td><td>Depends on platform, plan and data processing rules.</td><td>Designed for upload, processing, indexing and retrieval over user documents.</td></tr><tr><td>Sources and context</td><td>The answer is often not clearly tied to a concrete source.</td><td>Retrieval-first approach uses relevant document sections as context.</td></tr><tr><td>Privacy</td><td>Data is usually sent to an external provider.</td><td>Can run locally, in a private cloud or offline.</td></tr><tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Mostly public platform or API.</td><td>SaaS, private cloud, on-premise or local installation.</td></tr><tr><td>Database updates</td><td>The user usually does not control the model’s knowledge base.</td><td>New documentation can be intentionally added and indexed.</td></tr><tr><td>Draft preparation</td><td>Can write text, but without a specialized legal workflow.</td><td>Can prepare structured drafts based on documents and legal context.</td></tr><tr><td>Integrations</td><td>Limited to platform/API capabilities.</td><td>Can be adapted to DMS, ERP, CRM, legal databases and internal processes.</td></tr><tr><td>Cost control</td><td>Depends on subscriptions, API pricing and limits.</td><td>Can be optimized through local infrastructure and planned deployment.</td></tr></table></div>
  <h2>Conclusion</h2>
  <p>General-purpose AI assistants are excellent for general tasks and everyday productivity. Legal work requires more: local sources, privacy, document control, clear context and integration into an existing workflow.</p>
  <p>JusticeFusion is therefore a better fit for organizations that want to use AI in legal work without losing control over documents and without relying only on the general knowledge of public AI models.</p>
